Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.780 --> 00:00:20.390
COLLEEN SHOGAN: Good afternoon and
welcome to the Library of Congress.

00:00:20.390 --> 00:00:23.420
My name is Colleen Shogan and I'm
the Deputy Director of the National

00:00:23.420 --> 00:00:26.660
and International Outreach
at the Library.

00:00:26.660 --> 00:00:30.480
I'm excited to welcome our audience
inside the historic Members Room

00:00:30.480 --> 00:00:33.260
of the Jefferson Building
here on Capitol Hill.

00:00:33.260 --> 00:00:37.700
And I'm equally excited to welcome
our virtual audience joining us via

00:00:37.700 --> 00:00:39.040
live stream.

00:00:39.040 --> 00:00:45.290 position:56%
A video recording of this event will
be made available on our website.

00:00:45.290 --> 00:00:48.830
March is Women's History Month and
we're delighted to celebrate it

00:00:48.830 --> 00:00:53.170
with our new boss, Carla Hayden,
who happens to be the first woman

00:00:53.170 --> 00:00:56.170
and the first African American
to assume this position

00:00:56.170 --> 00:00:57.780
of Librarian of Congress.

00:00:57.780 --> 00:01:09.490
[applause] A few months
ago, I noticed a lot

00:01:09.490 --> 00:01:13.810
of innovative accomplishments have
begun to happen at the Library.

00:01:13.810 --> 00:01:15.180
So, what had changed?

00:01:15.180 --> 00:01:17.770 position:56%
Well, you all know what had changed.

00:01:17.770 --> 00:01:21.680
One woman and her leadership
can make a world of difference

00:01:21.680 --> 00:01:24.800
and today's panel is
living proof of that.

00:01:24.800 --> 00:01:27.350
Before we start, I would
like to thank the Library

00:01:27.350 --> 00:01:30.500
of Congress' Office
of EEO and Diversity

00:01:30.500 --> 00:01:33.460
for making this program
possible today.

00:01:33.460 --> 00:01:36.530
Now, I'd like to briefly introduce
our participants before turning it

00:01:36.530 --> 00:01:40.400
over to Dr. Hayden
for our discussion.

00:01:40.400 --> 00:01:43.020
Marin Alsop is the
12th musical director

00:01:43.020 --> 00:01:45.510
for the Baltimore Symphony
Orchestra.

00:01:45.510 --> 00:01:48.880
She is the first woman to head
a major American orchestra

00:01:48.880 --> 00:01:54.440 position:56%
and the only conductor to receive
the prestigious McArthur Fellowship.

00:01:54.440 --> 00:01:59.920
In 2010, she was inducted into
the Classical Music Hall of Fame.

00:01:59.920 --> 00:02:02.870
Previously, she was the
first principal conductor

00:02:02.870 --> 00:02:07.160
and then the musical director of
the Colorado Symphony Orchestra.

00:02:07.160 --> 00:02:09.190
In addition to her numerous awards,

00:02:09.190 --> 00:02:11.300
she has lead the Baltimore
Symphony Orchestra

00:02:11.300 --> 00:02:13.580
in key outreach initiatives,

00:02:13.580 --> 00:02:18.250
resulting in greater youth
musical awareness and appreciation.

00:02:18.250 --> 00:02:22.060
A student of Leonard Bernstein,
Alsop grew up in New York City

00:02:22.060 --> 00:02:26.270
and is a graduate of Yale
University and Julliard.

00:02:26.270 --> 00:02:28.070
Deborah Rutter is the
third President

00:02:28.070 --> 00:02:31.450
of the John F. Kennedy Center
for the Performing Arts.

00:02:31.450 --> 00:02:34.250
She is the first woman
to lead the center.

00:02:34.250 --> 00:02:37.130
In her capacity as
President, she is the Artistic

00:02:37.130 --> 00:02:40.090
and Administrative Director
of the Kennedy Center,

00:02:40.090 --> 00:02:43.240
managing all aspects
of the institution.

00:02:43.240 --> 00:02:46.640
Prior to her current position,
Ms. Rutter served as President

00:02:46.640 --> 00:02:48.360
of the Chicago Symphony Orchestra

00:02:48.360 --> 00:02:51.950
and Executive Director
of the Seattle Symphony.

00:02:51.950 --> 00:02:56.300
Yo Yo Ma credits her for making the
Chicago Orchestra more accessible

00:02:56.300 --> 00:03:00.050
to a wider audience through
innovative educational programs

00:03:00.050 --> 00:03:01.850
and community engagement,

00:03:01.850 --> 00:03:05.600
a model she is currently
replicating at the Kennedy Center.

00:03:05.600 --> 00:03:09.020
A native of Pennsylvania and Los
Angeles, Rutter is a graduate

00:03:09.020 --> 00:03:14.980
of Stanford University
and holds an MBA from USC.

00:03:14.980 --> 00:03:17.790
Molly Smith has served
as the Artistic Director

00:03:17.790 --> 00:03:20.530
of the Arena Stage since 1998.

00:03:20.530 --> 00:03:23.640
She has lead the invention of
the Arena Stage with a vision

00:03:23.640 --> 00:03:27.140
of creating a national
center for American artists.

00:03:27.140 --> 00:03:31.320
In 2010, the Washingtonian
famously referred to her

00:03:31.320 --> 00:03:35.000
as the unsinkable Molly Smith.

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:37.610
[laughter] During her leadership,
Arena has workshopped more

00:03:37.610 --> 00:03:41.070
than 100 productions,
produced 39 world premieres,

00:03:41.070 --> 00:03:44.460
and developed 9 projects
that have headed to Broadway.

00:03:44.460 --> 00:03:48.200
Before coming to Washington, Ms.
Smith was the Artistic Director

00:03:48.200 --> 00:03:51.360
of the Perseverance
Theater in Juneau, Alaska.

00:03:51.360 --> 00:03:55.060
She has served as the literary
advisor to the Sundance Theater Lab

00:03:55.060 --> 00:03:57.580
and formed the Arena
Stage Writers Council,

00:03:57.580 --> 00:04:00.940
whose members are leading
American playwrights.

00:04:00.940 --> 00:04:04.430 position:56%
Ms. Smith is a graduate of Catholic
University and has a Master's Degree

00:04:04.430 --> 00:04:07.510 position:56%
in Theater from American University.

00:04:07.510 --> 00:04:12.840 position:56%
Our moderator today is Carla Hayden,
the 14th Librarian of Congress.

00:04:12.840 --> 00:04:15.540
Please join me in welcoming
these distinguished women

00:04:15.540 --> 00:04:17.840
to the Library of Congress.

00:04:26.350 --> 00:04:34.330 position:56%
[applause] CARLA HAYDEN: I must tell
you that I've been the Librarian

00:04:34.330 --> 00:04:40.090
of Congress for 6 months and
I've had many many wonderful

00:04:40.090 --> 00:04:45.050
opportunities to interact with many
people, the collections and things,

00:04:45.050 --> 00:04:50.490
but I have to tell you, this
is super special for me.

00:04:50.490 --> 00:04:56.000
Because I have admired
Marin for a long time.

00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:02.230
I've gotten to be very
jealous of Deborah with that

00:05:02.230 --> 00:05:06.270
and that unsinkable Molly.

00:05:06.270 --> 00:05:09.280
Wow. So, it's wonderful
to be with you

00:05:09.280 --> 00:05:16.180
and to have what I hope will be
an honest and engaging discussion

00:05:16.180 --> 00:05:20.600
about being women in
the arts in particular

00:05:20.600 --> 00:05:24.590
but also in leadership positions.

00:05:24.590 --> 00:05:28.490
When I was introduced as
the first African American,

00:05:28.490 --> 00:05:33.440
which is of course very significant
in many ways for me personally,

00:05:33.440 --> 00:05:36.960
but being a woman in a
feminized profession,

00:05:36.960 --> 00:05:41.470 position:56%
where 85% of the workforce is female

00:05:41.470 --> 00:05:48.120
and the top leadership
does not reflect that fact,

00:05:48.120 --> 00:05:51.780
is really significant
for my profession

00:05:51.780 --> 00:05:53.540
and has been talked about.

00:05:53.540 --> 00:05:57.050
So, in my journey,
I had the beginning,

00:05:57.050 --> 00:05:59.720
not even knowing I was
going to be the Librarian -

00:05:59.720 --> 00:06:02.290
being an accidental
librarian, I call it.

00:06:02.290 --> 00:06:07.510
And I wondered how your journey
started in terms of the arts

00:06:07.510 --> 00:06:12.580
and then how did you make that
shift from being in the arts

00:06:12.580 --> 00:06:16.050
to arts management and leadership.

00:06:16.050 --> 00:06:18.300
When did that switch happen?

00:06:18.300 --> 00:06:21.990
Molly? MOLLY SMITH: Sure, sure.

00:06:21.990 --> 00:06:24.730
Well, I was interested
in arts and theater

00:06:24.730 --> 00:06:29.720
from when I was a little girl
and went to Catholic school

00:06:29.720 --> 00:06:34.280
and thought I was going to
go into a pre-law degree.

00:06:34.280 --> 00:06:38.630
And in the middle of traveling
through Europe at the age of 19

00:06:38.630 --> 00:06:41.680
with a backpack on, I decided
I was going to chuck all that,

00:06:41.680 --> 00:06:45.190
follow my heart and start
a theater in Alaska, ok?

00:06:45.190 --> 00:06:46.960
How crazy.

00:06:46.960 --> 00:06:48.600
Everybody thought I was crazy.

00:06:48.600 --> 00:06:52.630
So, in a sense, I moved from
artist to administrator right away,

00:06:52.630 --> 00:06:55.440
studied for the next 7
years to make that happen

00:06:55.440 --> 00:06:58.800
and then drug 50 USC
students to Alaska

00:06:58.800 --> 00:07:00.780
to start the Perseverance Theater.

00:07:00.780 --> 00:07:02.600
That's still alive and kicking now.

00:07:02.600 --> 00:07:09.130
It's 38 years old and then about 19
years ago, I came to Arena Stage.

00:07:09.130 --> 00:07:15.210 position:56%
So, I think I'm an artist whose
always wanted a home and often times

00:07:15.210 --> 00:07:17.270
when you want a home, it also means

00:07:17.270 --> 00:07:20.970
that you combine the
artistry with management.

00:07:20.970 --> 00:07:24.150
CARLA HAYDEN: Unsinkable.

00:07:24.150 --> 00:07:27.220
DEBORAH RUTTER: Great
name - Perseverance.

00:07:27.220 --> 00:07:29.990
CARLA HAYDEN: And Deborah, you
had an interesting way of getting

00:07:29.990 --> 00:07:31.580
into management from art.

00:07:31.580 --> 00:07:34.960
DEBORAH RUTTER: Well, actually
I think mine is very parallel.

00:07:34.960 --> 00:07:39.840
As a young person, I was
the beneficiary of a time

00:07:39.840 --> 00:07:42.760
when there was music
and art in schools.

00:07:42.760 --> 00:07:45.920
So, in my public school,
I had the opportunity

00:07:45.920 --> 00:07:48.900
to become a violinist, literally.

00:07:48.900 --> 00:07:52.120
My third grade teacher said,
"which instrument will you play?"

00:07:52.120 --> 00:07:54.790
Not, "would you like to
play, but will you play?"

00:07:54.790 --> 00:07:57.290
Played in orchestras
and followed my heart.

00:07:57.290 --> 00:08:00.930
Thought I was going to go
off and get some other job,

00:08:00.930 --> 00:08:05.360
not really knowing that there was
such a thing until I was in college

00:08:05.360 --> 00:08:11.620
and was introduced through
family friends to the field.

00:08:11.620 --> 00:08:14.350
And had my first Summer job,

00:08:14.350 --> 00:08:16.620
my first real summer job,
I had other summer jobs.

00:08:16.620 --> 00:08:19.430
My first real Summer job
was at the Hollywood bowl

00:08:19.430 --> 00:08:21.240
for the Los Angeles Philharmonic

00:08:21.240 --> 00:08:25.600
and I decided there was this
whole world of arts management.

00:08:25.600 --> 00:08:30.300
So, I took a pretty traditional
course in this way, but I would say

00:08:30.300 --> 00:08:34.170
that every decision I made in
my life was following my heart

00:08:34.170 --> 00:08:38.170
which needed to follow music
and I was never going to be able

00:08:38.170 --> 00:08:42.820
to spend enough time in a practice
room to be doing what she does.

00:08:42.820 --> 00:08:44.340
So, I get to support.

00:08:44.340 --> 00:08:47.060
Basically what I do is to
support what these two people do.

00:08:47.060 --> 00:08:49.290
CARLA HAYDEN: And that's great.

00:08:49.290 --> 00:08:50.590
And violin?

00:08:50.590 --> 00:08:55.340
MARIN ALSOP: I was a violinist
of course, but when I saw...

00:08:55.340 --> 00:08:59.170
My dad took me to a young
people's concert when I was 9.

00:08:59.170 --> 00:09:03.210
And I was getting in a lot of
trouble playing violin and trying

00:09:03.210 --> 00:09:05.340
to lead the orchestra from
the back of the violins

00:09:05.340 --> 00:09:07.660
at Julliard, pre college.

00:09:07.660 --> 00:09:10.060
So, then, this guy
came out to conduct

00:09:10.060 --> 00:09:12.180
who was jumping around
like a lunatic.

00:09:12.180 --> 00:09:14.780
And I turned to my dad and
said, "I could be the conductor

00:09:14.780 --> 00:09:18.400
because nobody's yelling at him."

00:09:18.400 --> 00:09:20.340
I was 9 and that was
Leonard Bernstein

00:09:20.340 --> 00:09:23.970
and eventually he became
my teacher and mentor.

00:09:23.970 --> 00:09:26.850
And he was my hero
for my entire life.

00:09:26.850 --> 00:09:30.700
But, I think as a conductor
and especially as a woman,

00:09:30.700 --> 00:09:33.180
in a field where there
were very few women,

00:09:33.180 --> 00:09:35.560
you have to be an entrepreneur

00:09:35.560 --> 00:09:37.660
because you don't have an
instrument as a conductor.

00:09:37.660 --> 00:09:40.880
Unless you can coerce 20
or 30 people are coming

00:09:40.880 --> 00:09:43.770 position:56%
over every day to practice with you.

00:09:43.770 --> 00:09:45.070
You don't have an instrument.

00:09:45.070 --> 00:09:49.130
So, it's all about what you can put
together and the way I learned how

00:09:49.130 --> 00:09:51.990
to conduct was by getting
all of my friends together

00:09:51.990 --> 00:09:53.290
and creating an orchestra.

00:09:53.290 --> 00:09:59.100 position:56%
So, I ran my own first orchestra and
learned hands on how to do marketing

00:09:59.100 --> 00:10:01.900
and build a board and all
those kinds of great things.

00:10:01.900 --> 00:10:04.470
So, now I'm just a really
annoying music director

00:10:04.470 --> 00:10:06.460
because I know a little
bit too much.

00:10:06.460 --> 00:10:08.500
I don't know enough
about management,

00:10:08.500 --> 00:10:10.570
but I know more than I should.

00:10:10.570 --> 00:10:15.620
[laughter] You're just
lucky you don't have me.

00:10:15.620 --> 00:10:22.520
CARLA HAYDEN: Are there special
challenges for women in the arts

00:10:22.520 --> 00:10:25.560
in terms of pay equity,
discrimination?

00:10:25.560 --> 00:10:27.010
Have you experienced that?

00:10:27.010 --> 00:10:31.000
MARIN ALSOP: You know that's
such a, from my perspective,

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:35.240
that's a question I'm asked
often, especially by journalists

00:10:35.240 --> 00:10:38.420
and I think it's, I
don't know the arts are

00:10:38.420 --> 00:10:40.660
such a difficult field anyway.

00:10:40.660 --> 00:10:44.850
It's really hard to
ascertain which aspect

00:10:44.850 --> 00:10:48.480
of what you're doing is causing
some kind of discrimination

00:10:48.480 --> 00:10:53.310
because there are so many ways
that you can run into obstacles.

00:10:53.310 --> 00:10:58.120
And I really think that,
I think that for me,

00:10:58.120 --> 00:11:05.900
I think part of my success is never
attributing any of my difficulties

00:11:05.900 --> 00:11:08.370
or rejections to being a woman.

00:11:08.370 --> 00:11:13.940
I think that, instead, I always
thought, "ok, I have to be better.

00:11:13.940 --> 00:11:16.840
Let me try to, how can I get
something positive out of this

00:11:16.840 --> 00:11:19.880
and learn from it and apply
it to what I'm doing?"

00:11:19.880 --> 00:11:22.100
So, that's how I've reacted to it.

00:11:22.100 --> 00:11:24.510
I don't know if you've
had similar experiences.

00:11:24.510 --> 00:11:29.870 position:56%
DEBORAH RUTTER: What I would imagine
for you and is true certainly

00:11:29.870 --> 00:11:32.860
in my experience is that
there are preconceptions

00:11:32.860 --> 00:11:36.450
about what people believe
should happen.

00:11:36.450 --> 00:11:39.400
You know, what will a
woman wear on a podium?

00:11:39.400 --> 00:11:43.190
What do women wear if they're
a soloist playing the violin

00:11:43.190 --> 00:11:46.540 position:56%
or the piano or anything, the flute?

00:11:46.540 --> 00:11:47.840
Whatever it is.

00:11:47.840 --> 00:11:51.010
So, there are just
gender expectations

00:11:51.010 --> 00:11:55.140
and those expectations are one
that we all have, male and female.

00:11:55.140 --> 00:11:56.440
MARIN ALSOP: Yes, that's true.

00:11:56.440 --> 00:11:59.710 position:56%
DEBORAH RUTTER: And that we all sort
of have to deal with and understand.

00:11:59.710 --> 00:12:02.890
And those are the kinds
of expectations

00:12:02.890 --> 00:12:04.840
that are difficult to overcome.

00:12:04.840 --> 00:12:08.250
Because if you don't fall
in line, then there's going

00:12:08.250 --> 00:12:10.680
to be a discussion, "well,
she didn't fall in line."

00:12:10.680 --> 00:12:17.820
So, how many men have to
buy gowns to do their work?

00:12:17.820 --> 00:12:19.120
I have to buy them.

00:12:19.120 --> 00:12:20.850
People ask me, "what are
you wearing tonight?"

00:12:20.850 --> 00:12:22.890
When's the last time
somebody asked a man,

00:12:22.890 --> 00:12:24.220
what he was wearing to an event?

00:12:24.220 --> 00:12:26.410
CARLA HAYDEN: Especially
to a black tie event.

00:12:26.410 --> 00:12:27.880
DEBORAH RUTTER: Exactly.

00:12:27.880 --> 00:12:32.470
So, I think Marin's
comment is right.

00:12:32.470 --> 00:12:36.420
The arts is a different
kind of business.

00:12:36.420 --> 00:12:42.340 position:56%
And so the interactions that we have
with our bosses, the interactions

00:12:42.340 --> 00:12:43.780
that we have with our patrons,

00:12:43.780 --> 00:12:47.680
with our potential patrons are
all a little bit different.

00:12:47.680 --> 00:12:52.240
But there's always this issue
of how do people treat women

00:12:52.240 --> 00:12:55.350
and men what the expectations
are I think that's the part

00:12:55.350 --> 00:12:57.390
that you are constantly
working to overcome.

00:12:57.390 --> 00:13:01.500
MOLLY SMITH: There are
pretty shocking statistics

00:13:01.500 --> 00:13:04.560
in theater as far as men and women.

00:13:04.560 --> 00:13:07.790
Of the major theaters
in the United States

00:13:07.790 --> 00:13:12.030
and there are 1800 theaters
now that really started

00:13:12.030 --> 00:13:15.500
by three intrepid women which
really included Zelda Fitch Handler

00:13:15.500 --> 00:13:18.860
of the Arena Stage 70 years ago.

00:13:18.860 --> 00:13:21.740
And there are large theaters
and of the large theaters

00:13:21.740 --> 00:13:27.950
and of the large theaters, only
twenty percent are run by women.

00:13:27.950 --> 00:13:34.510
In terms of plays that are
produced by these 1800 theaters,

00:13:34.510 --> 00:13:37.820
only 22% are written by women.

00:13:37.820 --> 00:13:40.290
So, let that penny drop.

00:13:40.290 --> 00:13:42.080
Start to look at that.

00:13:42.080 --> 00:13:46.120
When you realize that that's
happening at the leadership level,

00:13:46.120 --> 00:13:47.500
that means it's happening

00:13:47.500 --> 00:13:52.640
because boards are leaning
more into male candidates.

00:13:52.640 --> 00:13:58.380 position:56%
It means that headhunters perhaps
have more males who are headhunters.

00:13:58.380 --> 00:14:03.350
It means that we have to do
much more in terms of mentorship

00:14:03.350 --> 00:14:07.370
of young women who are
coming up and support them.

00:14:07.370 --> 00:14:11.490
In terms of changing the
paradigm, it's a paradigm shift.

00:14:11.490 --> 00:14:14.030
I mean, I would agree with
what everybody else has said,

00:14:14.030 --> 00:14:17.210
but then I think there's the
other piece that just has to do

00:14:17.210 --> 00:14:22.210
with statistical difficulties
of what women face

00:14:22.210 --> 00:14:24.110
in terms of leadership positions.

00:14:24.110 --> 00:14:26.420
It is that you have to be better.

00:14:26.420 --> 00:14:29.550 position:56%
Wasn't it Flo Kennedy that said,
"Fortunately, that's not difficult"?

00:14:29.550 --> 00:14:36.000
[laughter] That was a very
funny line, but it's complicated

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:40.010
and I think the idea of
mentorship is so powerful.

00:14:40.010 --> 00:14:42.010
Because it is the step in.

00:14:42.010 --> 00:14:43.910
It is the door opening.

00:14:43.910 --> 00:14:48.050 position:56%
Even for me, more than education, it
takes you in a whole other direction

00:14:48.050 --> 00:14:50.170
because mentorship is a one

00:14:50.170 --> 00:14:53.690
on one relationship
that shows you the path.

00:14:53.690 --> 00:14:58.550
And I think without mentors for me
like Joy Zimmerman and Paula Vogel,

00:14:58.550 --> 00:15:02.220
who's a brilliant playwright, I
don't know if I would be here.

00:15:02.220 --> 00:15:07.260
MARIN ALSOP: The statistics in
classical music are even more dire.

00:15:07.260 --> 00:15:11.800
I think of our programming,
is it 5% by women composers?

00:15:11.800 --> 00:15:14.150
It's really and I'm
sure for conductors,

00:15:14.150 --> 00:15:17.500
it ranges around there as well.

00:15:17.500 --> 00:15:22.180
